        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-10-08 05:38:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nIs this fix only for HAVE_VM_OP_FAULT case? What if the kernel doesn't have .fault operation?\n\nFor the kernel which having .fault operation, I don't see why we have to unlock the page vvp_io_kernel_fault() and acquire the page lock again immediately in vvp_io_fault_start(), why not just unlock the page after cl_page_find() in vvp_io_fault_start()?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "5b980209b59cb1c9ab60e72d2a79f96d9aa0dcee",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-10-10 17:08:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nto niu: for nopage case, it will return a truncated page and kernel is supposed to catch this case when it locks the page and installs pte.\n\nIf we revise vvp_io_kernel_fault() to return a locked page, we will have trouble to unlock page after cl_page_find(), that's to say, for .fault case, we need to clear VM_FAULT_LOCKED bit and one extra '#ifndef HAVE_VM_OP_FAULT' will be needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a576844134643c7b89e0b2e62003d3f2ca79bb9b",
      "author": {
